    <exercise xml:id="STAT-bcaqiUydWW-parts" original="STAT/modules/m79621/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>
              <em>P</em>(<m>x</m> = 4) = ________</li>
            <li>
              <em>P</em>(<m>x</m> ≥ 5) = ________</li>
            <li>On average, how long would you expect a new hire to stay with the company?</li>
            <li>What does the column “<em>P</em>(<m>x</m>)” sum to?</li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li />
            <li>.10 + .05 = .15</li>
            <li />
            <li>1</li>
          </ol>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="STAT-hnikGXdQl1-parts" original="STAT/modules/m79621/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>Define the random variable <em>X</em>.</li>
            <li>What is the probability the baker will sell more than one batch? <em>P</em>(<m>x</m> &gt; 1) = ________</li>
            <li>What is the probability the baker will sell exactly one batch? <em>P</em>(<m>x</m> = 1) = ________</li>
            <li>On average, how many batches should the baker make?</li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li />
            <li>.35 + .40 + .10 = .85</li>
            <li />
            <li>1(.15) + 2(.35) + 3(.40) + 4(.10) = .15 + .70 + 1.20 + .40 = 2.45</li>
          </ol>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="STAT-QmVHlPmo36-parts" original="STAT/modules/m79621/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>Define the random variable <em>X</em>.</li>
            <li>Construct a probability distribution table for the data.</li>
            <li>We know that for a probability distribution function to be discrete, it must have two characteristics. One is that the sum of the probabilities is one. What is the other characteristic?</li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="STAT-GqC3IY1FOe-parts" original="STAT/modules/m79621/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>Define the random variable <em>X</em>.</li>
            <li>What values does <em>x</em> take on?</li>
            <li>Construct a PDF table.</li>
            <li>Find the probability that Javier volunteers for fewer than three events each month. <em>P</em>(<m>x</m> &lt; 3) = ________</li>
            <li>Find the probability that Javier volunteers for at least one event each month. <em>P</em>(<m>x</m> &gt; 0) = ________</li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>Let <m>X</m> = the number of events Javier volunteers for each month.</li>
            <li />
            <li />
            <li />
            <li>1 – .05 = .95</li>
          </ol>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="STAT-dwogMfG54w" original="STAT/modules/m79621/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <p>Suppose that the PDF for the number of years it takes to earn a bachelor of science (B.S.) degree is given in <xref ref="STAT-pvJOt8eyGt" />.</p>
